  "title": "Hyperkalaemia",
  "version_date": null,
  "section": "Medical",
  "content_markdown": "#### Assessment\nConsider hyperkalaemia in these situations:\n\n- Renal failure / dialysis.\n- Crush syndrome, including situations of prolonged unconsciousness.\n- Occasionally – diabetic ketoacidosis.\n\n**ECG signs are unreliable, frequently do not follow expected progressions, and do not always show good correlation with serum potassium levels.** However arrhythmias, especially bradycardias, are common. \n\nMonitor the ECG for signs of hyperkalaemia, which may include:\n\n- Tall, peaked T waves.\n- No P waves.\n- Wide QRS.\n- Sine wave pattern.\n- VT / VF / asystole.\n**Note:** treatment is determined by patient presentation, ECG changes and the clinical setting.\n\n#### Management#### ECG Changes are Present\n- Salbutamol.\n- **ICP:** Calcium chloride.\n- **ICP:** Sodium bicarbonate.\n- IV fluid as per CMG 14 Shock and Hypoperfusion.\n- Caution in patients who are fluid restricted for medical reasons.\n#### ECG Changes Persist\n- **ICP:** If ECG changes persist after 10-15 minutes post medication: \n- Repeat calcium chloride and sodium bicarbonate doses once each. \n\n#### Cardiac Arrest Secondary to Hyperkalaemia\nIn cardiac arrest thought to be secondary to hyperkalaemia (i.e. hyperkalaemia is thought to be the cause of the arrest):\n\n- Cardiac arrest management as per relevant CMG with the addition of: \n- **ICP:** Early sodium bicarbonate - **ICP:** Calcium chloride",
